* ============================================================================
* TLV7034 (quad) -- TI PSpice macromodel
* ============================================================================
* PROVENANCE (read this before trusting any result derived from this model):
*
*   Source: TI literature SLVMDH3, listed on the TLV7034 product folder as
*           "TLV7034 PSpice Model". Downloaded from ti.com/lit/zip/slvmdh3.
*   The zip contains a single netlist named tlv7031.lib. That is expected:
*   the TLV7034 is four copies of the TLV703x die, so TI ships one model for
*   the family and the quad is instantiated four times. The subcircuit inside
*   is .SUBCKT TLV7031.
*
* DISCREPANCIES vs the TLV703x datasheet (SLVSE13J), all verified in TB10:
*
*   1. The file header says "Part: TLV7011" and "Datasheet: SLVSDM5F" even
*      though the subcircuit is named TLV7031. TI appears to have derived the
*      TLV703x model from the TLV701x one. This matters for exactly one
*      number, hysteresis (see 2). Everything else was checked in TB10.
*
*   2. HYSTERESIS: the model hard-codes VHYS = 7 mV (V_V1 N00366 0 7m inside
*      TOPLEVELSCHEMATIC, feeding the HPA_COMPHYS block). The TLV703x
*      datasheet specifies 10 mV typ, 3 mV min, 25 mV max. 7 mV is therefore
*      CONSERVATIVE against typ and still well above the 3 mV minimum.
*      Chatter conclusions drawn with this model are pessimistic, not
*      optimistic, which is the safe direction.
*
*   3. SUPPLY RANGE: the model's SUPPLYRANGE block enforces 1.65 V <= Vs <=
*      5.5 V; the datasheet allows 1.6 V to 6.5 V. Vs = 3.3 V sits comfortably
*      inside both, so this never trips here.
*
*   4. INPUT RANGE: the INPUTRANGE block flags out-of-range only when an input
*      exceeds an ABSOLUTE 6 V, or falls below V- - 0.3 V. Note it is NOT
*      referenced to V+. This is the whole reason the part fixes the board:
*      the LM2901 model's INPUTRANGE enforced Vcc-2.0 (= 1.30 V at 3.3 V) and
*      the 1.65 V reference sat above it. Datasheet VCM is V- to V+ + 0.1.
*      The model is thus slightly OPTIMISTIC above V+ + 0.1; we never operate
*      there (max input is N_SUM at ~3.10 V), so it does not affect any
*      conclusion. TB10(B) measures this directly.
*
*   5. The out-of-range flag uses the same mid-supply (MID_SUPPLY / S3 switch)
*      mechanism as the LM2901 model: if it ever trips, OUT is FORCED to
*      Vs/2 = 1.65 V. As with the LM339 work, a 1.65 V output from this model
*      is a "model invalid here" flag, NOT a physical prediction. TB10 exists
*      to prove the flag stays untripped across our whole operating range.
*
*   6. The output stage is two ideal-ish BJTs (NPN1/PNP1, LEVEL=1, RC=1,
*      RB=850). VOL/VOH fidelity is therefore modelled, not characterised.
*      TB10(C) compares the model's VOL at 3 mA against the datasheet's
*      250 mV typ / 350 mV max before any LED current is quoted.
*
* MODIFICATIONS: none. The netlist below is byte-identical to TI's, except
* that CRLF line endings were converted to LF. No content was edited.
* ============================================================================
*
* WRAPPER: TI's port order is (IN+ IN- OUT V+ V-). Every other comparator in
* this project (LM2901) uses (IN+ IN- Vcc GND OUT). Rather than silently
* re-order ports at each call site -- an easy way to produce a wrong answer
* that still simulates -- the wrapper below adapts TI's subcircuit to the
* house port order. Call TLV7034; do not call TLV7031 directly.
*
.SUBCKT TLV7034 IN+ IN- Vcc GND OUT
X1 IN+ IN- OUT Vcc GND TLV7031
.ENDS TLV7034
*
* ---------------- TI's netlist, verbatim from SLVMDH3 ----------------
* PSpice Model Editor - Version 17.2.0
*$
* TLV7011
